🌿 ब्रह्मगीता – ऐन्दवोपाख्यानम् (सर्ग १७८)
भाग १ : मूर्त और अमूर्त का रहस्य
Brahma Gītā – Aindava Upākhyāna (Sarga 178)
Part One: The Mystery of Form and the Formless
मूल श्लोक
श्रीराम उवाच
पदार्था द्विविधाः सन्ति मूर्तामूर्ता जगत्त्रये।
यत्र सप्रतिघाः केचित् केचिदप्रतिघा अपि॥१॥
तानिहाप्रतिघानाहुर्नान्योन्यं वेल्लयन्ति ये।
तांश्च सप्रतिघानाहुरन्योन्यं वेल्लयन्ति ये॥२॥
इह सप्रतिघानां तु दृष्टमन्योन्यवेल्लनम्।
न त्वप्रतिघरूपाणां केषांचिदपि किंचन॥३॥
तत्र संवेदनं नाम यदिदं चन्द्रमण्डले।
इतः पतत्यप्रतिघं तत्सर्वेणानुभूयते॥४॥
🌿 हिन्दी भावार्थ
श्रीरामचन्द्रजी एक अत्यन्त गम्भीर प्रश्न उठाते हैं।
इस संसार में दो प्रकार के पदार्थ दिखाई देते हैं—
मूर्त (साकार) और अमूर्त (निराकार)।
मूर्त वे हैं जो एक-दूसरे से टकराते हैं—जैसे शरीर, पत्थर, वृक्ष, पर्वत आदि।
अमूर्त वे हैं जिनमें प्रतिघात नहीं होता—जैसे विचार, स्मृति, अनुभूति तथा चेतना।
यहाँ "अमूर्त" का अर्थ अभी परमब्रह्म नहीं है, बल्कि ऐसा तत्त्व है जिसे स्पर्श या आघात नहीं किया जा सकता।
श्रीराम कहते हैं—
हम संसार में पत्थर को पत्थर से टकराते देखते हैं, शरीर को शरीर से टकराते देखते हैं; किन्तु किसी ने कभी ज्ञान, विचार या चेतना को किसी वस्तु से टकराते नहीं देखा।
फिर भी चेतना चन्द्रमा को जान लेती है।
जब हम चन्द्रमा को देखते हैं, तब हमारी आँख वहाँ नहीं पहुँचती, शरीर भी वहाँ नहीं जाता; फिर भी चन्द्रमा का अनुभव हो जाता है।
यह कैसी अद्भुत शक्ति है?
यदि चेतना स्वयं निराकार है, तो वह इस मूर्त जगत का अनुभव कैसे करती है?
इसी जिज्ञासा से यह दिव्य संवाद प्रारम्भ होता है।
🌿 English Reflection
Sri Rama begins with one of the deepest philosophical questions in Vedanta.
There appear to be two kinds of realities:
Form and the Formless.
Forms occupy space.
They collide with one another.
Bodies, stones, mountains, and trees belong to this category.
But awareness, thought, memory, and understanding possess no measurable form.
No one has ever seen consciousness strike an object.
Yet consciousness effortlessly knows the moon.
When we gaze at the moon, our body remains on Earth.
Nothing physical travels there.
Still, the moon is immediately present in our experience.
How does the formless know the formed?
This is the profound inquiry Sri Rama now places before Sage Vasiṣṭha.
🌿 Vedantic Insight
The question itself reveals an assumption.
It assumes that Consciousness and matter are two separate realities needing to be connected.
Sri Vasiṣṭha will gradually dissolve this assumption.
His teaching is not that Consciousness somehow enters matter.
Rather, he will reveal that matter itself is an appearance within Consciousness.
Just as mountains, rivers, bodies, and skies in a dream are nothing but the dreamer's own mind, so too this waking universe shines in Consciousness alone.
When this is understood, the ancient problem—
"How does Consciousness control matter?"
simply disappears.
There are never two independent realities.
There is only One appearing as many.
🌿 Practical Contemplation
Whenever you say,
"I see the world,"
pause for a moment and inquire:
Who is this "I" that knows?
Is it merely the eyes?
Is it the brain?
Or is it the silent Awareness because of which both eyes and brain are themselves known?
Vedanta invites us not merely to observe the world,
but to discover the Knower.
🌸 Living Vedanta Library Conclusion
The journey toward Self-realization begins not by rejecting the world,
but by questioning our assumptions about it.
Sri Rama's inquiry is our own inquiry.
How can the Formless know form?
Sri Vasiṣṭha's answer will unfold gradually.
Ultimately, he will reveal that the body appears in Consciousness—
Consciousness never enters the body.
The many shine because of the One.
The changing is illumined by the Changeless.
The visible rests upon the Invisible.
That Invisible Awareness is your own true Self.
